amazon_bestsellers

Jun

2022-09-25

Dataset Description

The dataset used for this project is the Amazon Top 50 Bestselling Books from 2009-2019 extracted from kaggle.
The columns in this dataset consist of:

  1. Name - The name of the book
  2. Author - The writer of the book
  3. User Rating - The rating of the book from a scale of 1-5
  4. Reviews - The total count of reviews for the book
  5. Price - The cost of the book in USD (As of 13/10/2020)
  6. Year - The year(s) it was ranked on bestseller
  7. Genre - Fiction or Non-fiction

Project Description

For this project, I will be performing Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) and will visualize the data using the ggplot2 library in R. Here are some of the questions Ill be answering throughout the project:

  1. What is the relationship between user rating and other variables?
  2. Which genres become bestsellers more often?
  3. Which authors have the most best sellers?
  4. What is the trend of the genres over the years?
  5. Distribution of the ratings
  6. What are the top 5 multiple bestseller books?
  7. What are the top 10 most expensive bestseller books?
  8. Who are the authors with the highest prices on average?

Top 10 Most Expensive Bestsellers

highest_price_books <- bestsellers[order(-bestsellers$Price),]
highest_price_books <- highest_price_books %>% # removes duplicate entries over multiple years
  distinct(Name, Author, Price)

highest_price_books <- highest_price_books %>% # Select top 10 highest priced books 
  top_n(10)
## Selecting by Price
name_genre_df <- select(bestsellers, Name, Genre)

# Inner join top 10 books and bestsellers to add Genre to highest_price_books
highest_price_books <- inner_join(x=highest_price_books, y=name_genre_df, by="Name")
highest_price_books <- unique(highest_price_books) # remove duplicate entries over multiple years from the inner join

highest_price_books %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=reorder(Name, Price), y = Price, fill=Genre)) + 
  geom_bar(stat='identity', width=0.7) +
  geom_text(aes(label=Price), nudge_y=6, alpha=0.8) + 
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title="Top 10 Highest Priced Bestsellers") +
  xlab("Book Title") + 
  ylab("Price in USD")

From this bar graph, we can see the top 10 highest priced books with the the highest price being $105 and the lowest being $36. Additionally, we can see that out of the 10 books, six are Non-Fiction and four are Fiction.

Relationship between User Rating and Other Independent Variables

# prepare data frame for correlation matrix as attributes should be numerical
corr_df <- bestsellers %>% 
  select(`User Rating`, Reviews, Price, Year, Genre)

corr_df$Genre <- as.numeric(factor(corr_df$Genre)) # 2 = Nonfiction, 1 = Fiction

corr <- corr_df %>% # Correlation Matrix
  cor()

ggcorrplot(corr, lab=TRUE)

From the correlation matrix, we can see that there is no linear correlation between User Rating and Reviews. We can also see that there are very weak negative correlations between (User Rating, Price) and (User Rating, Genre) and very weak positive correlations between User Rating and Year.

# Average price by genre over the years
avg_price_by_genre <- bestsellers %>% 
  group_by(Genre, Year) %>% 
  summarize(mean = mean(Price))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'Genre'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
avg_price_by_genre %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=Year, y=mean, fill=Genre)) + 
  geom_bar(stat='identity', position='dodge') +
  xlim(2009, 2019) + 
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=c(2009, 2011, 2013, 2015, 2017, 2019)) +
  labs(title="Average Price by Genre Over the Years") +
  ylab("Average Price in USD") + 
  xlab("Year")
## Scale for 'x' is already present. Adding another scale for 'x', which will
## replace the existing scale.

From this graph, we can see that Non-fiction books had a higher average price than Fiction books with the exception of 2009. Additionally, we can see that the average price for Non-fiction books peaked in 2014 and has been decreasing since then. The average price of fiction books peaked in 2009 and has also been steadily decreasing since then with the exception of a few minor fluctuations.

From this graph, we can see that Fiction novels had a much higher number of reviews than Non-Fiction books.

Conclusion

In this notebook, we cleaned up and analyzed the top 50 bestselling books on amazon dataset. From Exploratory Data Analysis, our findings showed:

  • The majority of bestsellers had over a 4.0 rating, with only a select few with a lower rating than that.
  • There were 28 books with a 4.9 rating, which was the highest a book was rated.
  • Dav Pilkey wrote the most number of bestsellers with a 4.9 rating (6 books).
  • Jeff Kinney (Author of Diary of a Wimpy Kid) wrote the most bestsellers overall (12 books).
  • There were 240 Fiction and 310 Non-Fiction bestsellers through out 2009-2019.
  • The highest priced bestseller is Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders, 5th Edition with a price of $105.
  • There were no strong correlations between User Rating and other attributes (Reviews, Price, Year, Genre)
  • The most a book became a bestseller is Publication Manual of the American Psychological Association, 6th Edition with it being a bestseller for 10 years
  • There were more Non-Fiction books than Fiction books in the top 50 bestsellers for all years with the exception of 2014.
  • Non-fiction books had a higher average price for all years with the exception of 2009.
  • Fiction books had more reviews than that of Non Fiction books.

From this analysis, we can see that it may be more favorable for a publisher to publish a nonfiction book over a fiction book. However, it is important to consider that Fiction books had more user interaction with a higher number of reviews.
